North Korea says 'no way' unilateral disarmament without trust
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that sanctions are still being maintained to deepen its mistrust of the United States and that in this situation, there is no way that it will unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho, speaking at an annual session of the UN General Assembly, said North Korea had taken “many goodwill measures” over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test bases and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“However, we don’t see a similar move from the US side,” he said.
“If we can’t trust the American side, then we won’t be able to confidently guarantee our national security, and in such a situation, there’s no way we unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s familiar complaint that Washington refused to denuclearize “stage by stage” and that North Korea would receive the corresponding benefit of taking it step by step, his remarks this time have a notable point of not rejecting the unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang has refused before.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an incumbent U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12. In this statement, Kim pledged to work toward “nuclear disarmament on the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump promised security for North Korea.
North Korea is still trying to find a way to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States insists it must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington also opposes calls for easing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increased pressure by sanctions to achieve its goals in a coercive way, even opposing the ‘declaration of an end to war’,” Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions can bring us down on our knees is just a dream of people who don’t understand us.
“But the problem is that the sanctions that are still in place continue to lose our trust.”
Ri did not mention plans to hold a second summit between Kim and Trump, as the U.S. leader presented at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, he referred to three meetings between Kim and South Korean President Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: “If the negotiator on the issue of nuclear disarmament is South Korea, not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula will not be in the same stalemate as it is today.”
Ri’s tone, however, was different from last year, when he told the General Assembly that North Korea’s missile launch on the U.S. mainland was inevitable on a suicide mission after Trump called Kim “the Rocket Man.”
Last year at the United Nations, Trump threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, but this year he praised Kim for taking steps to disarm, but Trump also stressed that there is still a lot of work to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not set a deadline for this: “Two years, three years, or just five months is no problem.”
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its efforts.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The Security Council sanctions must continue to be vigorously and uncompromisingly enforced until we can confirm the result of complete denuclearization, ultimately, with verifiable evidence.”
The Security Council has agreed to step up sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to halt funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo held talks with Ri on the sidelines of official UN General Assembly meetings and said he would visit Pyongyang again next month in preparation for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the end result is not very good.
He left Pyongyang after a visit in July and said the talks had made certain progress, but just hours later, North Korea accused the foreign minister of making “black society-like demands.”
North Korea has pledged to take part in a meeting with South Korean President Moon Jae-In this month aimed at dismantling a missile test base and a nuclear complex if the United States makes a “similar move.”
He said Chairman Kim directed that the “similar move” he was seeking was the security assurance that Trump had pledged during the talks in Singapore and moved toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take full rest course
In an effort to combat the culture of machine-pressure learning, with ‘night owls’ drinking coffee instead of water, a new course at Harvard University this year has encouraged all college students to sleep more.
Students who study at this world’s number one university often don’t know the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at the Women’s Hospital and Brigham who designed the course, believes it to be the first of its kind in the United States.
The inspiration for starting this course came after he attended a talk about the impact of sleep deprivation on the learning process.
“After the talk, a female student came to me and said, ‘Why did you know this in the last year?’
She said no one told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course was introduced for the first time this year, explaining to students how the importance of good sleep habits improves academic and athletic performance while improving their overall health.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding students with severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course consists of a range of interactive tasks.
In a section with a dorm room image, students can click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise machines, and books to learn about how caffeine, light, and sleep deprivation affect athletic performance, as well as the importance of forming bedtime habits.
In another section, participants were asked how long-term sleep deprivation may increase their risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then, the university campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know that this course cannot immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke,” Czeisler added.
The culture of “night owls” pride still exists, he said, while modern technologies and increasing pressure on students to sleep deprivation are an increasingly serious problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep, good sleep quality should become a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety – even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep causes the brain to fall into a state of hunger, leading us to be constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying biology, chemistry and physics, helped Czeisler design the course, and he also took one of last year’s classes in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course helped him ‘open his eyes’ and inspired him to make an effort to call for a course across the school.
He hoped that the next step would be to ask all postgraduate students to join a similar degree program before starting to compete in the main course.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students consider when setting an alarm for bedtime, waking hours, and be aware of the harmful effects of ‘green light’ emitted by electronic displays and LEDs, which can cause disturbances in your circadian rhythms, resulting in difficulty sleeping.
