This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management activities of organisms, such as planting pastures and the best way to conserve forests for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect bat bean truss and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting systems, fly trap paper, some chemical treatments for building materials, as well as pet cat attacks can also pose a risk to bats.
Bats are not completely blind.
However, due to the habit of hunting at night, the ears are more useful than the eyes when stalking and catching prey.
They use an extremely sophisticated echo positioning technique to identify obstacles on the flight path.
NTS is responsible for taking care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, while attaching special importance to bats.
