“We have a lot of old buildings, a lot of trees and a good living environment.
But there is still a lot of mystery about bats, so work here and at other facilities will help us better understand what bats need to grow further.”
He stressed the importance of examining bat life before conserving in the lands, because the accidental destruction of their breeding truss can kill up to 400 offspring and vomit offspring, almost completely destroying the population.
Bats are protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their bean truss.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an employee of the Scottish Bat Conservation Foundation, encouraged the community to help.
“We still need to learn more about bats, and with many species, we can’t know how far apart their populations are.”
